# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: automotive-industry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The **1970s energy crisis** occurred when the Western world, particularly the United States, Canada, Western Europe, Australia, and New Zealand, experienced substantial petroleum shortages as well as elevated prices.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The two worst crises of this period were the 1973 oil crisis and the 1979 oil crisis, when, respectively, the Yom Kippur War and the Iranian Revolution triggered interruptions in Middle Eastern oil exports.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The crisis began to unfold as petroleum production in the United States and some other parts of the world peaked in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] World oil production per capita began a long-term decline after 1979.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The oil crises prompted the first shift towards energy-saving (in particular, fossil fuel-saving) technologies.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The major industrial centers of the world were forced to contend with escalating issues related to petroleum supply.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Western countries relied on the resources of countries in the Middle East and other parts of the world.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The crisis led to stagnant economic growth in many countries as oil prices surged.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Although there were genuine concerns with supply, part of the run-up in prices resulted from the perception of a crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The combination of stagnant growth and price inflation during this era led to the coinage of the term *stagflation*.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] By the 1980s, both the recessions of the 1970s and adjustments in local economies to become more efficient in petroleum usage, controlled demand sufficiently for petroleum prices worldwide to return to more sustainable levels.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The period was not uniformly negative for all economies.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Petroleum-rich countries in the Middle East benefited from increased prices and the slowing production in other areas of the world.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Some other countries, such as Norway, Mexico, and Venezuela, benefited as well.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] In the United States, Texas and Alaska, as well as some other oil-producing areas, experienced major economic booms due to soaring oil prices even as most of the rest of the nation struggled with the stagnant economy.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Many of these economic gains, however, came to a halt as prices stabilized and dropped in the 1980s.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East has existed since Israel's declaration of independence in 1948, including a number of wars.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1956 Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked when Israel's southern port of Eilat was blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to Anglo-French investors.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] One of the objectives of the Anglo-French-Israeli invasion was the removal of President Gamal Abdel Nasser who was aligning with the Soviet Union.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt's closure of the Suez Canal for eight years after Israel occupied the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975 after the 1973 Yom Kippur War, when Egypt tried and failed to take back the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel in the war after learning that the Soviet Union, was aiding Syria and Egypt in the war.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The real price of petroleum was stable in the 1970 timeframe, but there had been a sharp increase in American imports, putting a strain on American balance of trade, alongside other developed nations.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] During the 1960s, petroleum production in some of the world's top producers with extraction technology at the time began to peak.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] West Germany reached its production peak in 1966, Venezuela and the United States in 1970, and Iran in 1974.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Canada's conventional oil production peaked around the same time (though non-conventional production later helped revive Canadian production to some degree).
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The worldwide production per capita peaked soon afterward.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Although production in other parts of the world was increasing, the peaks in these regions began to put substantial upward pressure on world oil prices.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Equally as important, control of the oil supply became an increasingly important problem as countries like West Germany and the U.S. became increasingly dependent on foreign suppliers for this key resource.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 oil crisis was a direct consequence of the U.S production peak in late 1960 and the beginning of 1971 (and shortages, especially for heating oil, started from there).
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The "embargo" as described below is the "practical name" given to the crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] For the main Arab producers, the "embargo" supposedly allowed them to show to "the Arab street" that they were doing something to support Egypt in reclaiming its territory in Sinai and Gaza.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] In reality, it was more a desire to punish the U.S for re-supplying Israel with weapons during the Yom Kippur War, after the Soviet Union re-supplied Syria and Egypt with weapons.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] In real market terms (number of barrels) the embargo was almost a non-event, as it was only conducted by a few countries, against a few countries.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The embargo was never effective from Saudi Arabia towards the US, as reported by James E.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Akins in interview at 24:10 in the documentary "la face cachée du pétrole part 2".
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Akins, who audited US capacity for Nixon after US peak, was US ambassador in Saudi Arabia at that time.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Lawrence Rocks and Richard Runyon captured the unfolding of these events at the time in The Energy Crisis book.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] OAPEC declared it would limit or stop oil shipments to the United States and other countries if they supported Israel in the conflict.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] With the US actions seen as initiating the oil embargo, the long-term possibility of embargo-related high oil prices, disrupted supply and recession, created a strong rift within NATO; both European countries and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from the US Middle East policy.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Arab oil producers had also linked the end of the embargo with successful US efforts to create peace in the Middle East, which complicated the situation.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] To address these developments, the Nixon Administration began parallel negotiations with both Arab oil producers to end the embargo, and with Egypt, Syria, and Israel to arrange an Israeli pull back from the Sinai and the Golan Heights after the fighting stopped.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] By January 18, 1974, Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was sufficient to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] By May, Israel agreed to withdraw from parts of the Golan Heights close to the Syrian border.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Independently, the OPEC members agreed to use their leverage over the world price-setting mechanism for oil to stabilize their real incomes by raising world oil prices.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] This action followed several years of steep income declines after the recent failure of negotiations with the major Western oil companies earlier in the month.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] For the most part, industrialized economies relied on crude oil, and OPEC was a major supplier.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Because of the dramatic inflation experienced during this period, a popular economic theory has been that these price increases were to blame, as being suppressive of economic activity.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] However, the causality stated by this theory is often questioned.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The targeted countries responded with a wide variety of new, and mostly permanent, initiatives to contain their further dependency.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 "oil price shock", along with the 1973–1974 stock market crash, have been regarded as the first event since the Great Depression to have a persistent economic effect.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] A crisis emerged in the United States in 1979 during the wake of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Amid massive protests, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, fled his country in early 1979, allowing the Ayatollah Khomeini to gain control.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The protests shattered the Iranian oil sector.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] While the new regime resumed oil exports, it was inconsistent and at a lower volume, forcing prices to go up.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Dr.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Mana Alotaiba increased production to offset the decline, and the overall loss in production was about 4 percent.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] However, a widespread panic resulted, driving the price far higher than would be expected under normal circumstances.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] In 1980, following the Iraqi invasion of Iran, oil production in Iran nearly stopped, and Iraq's oil production was severely cut as well.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Afterwards, oil prices began a decline as other countries began to fill the production shortfalls from Iran and Iraq.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 and 1979 energy crisis had caused petroleum prices to peak in 1980 at over US$35 per barrel (US$137 in today's dollars).
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Following these events slowing industrial economies and stabilization of supply and demand caused prices to begin falling in the 1980s.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The glut began in the early 1980s as a result of slowed economic activity in industrial countries (due to the 1973 and 1979 energy crises) and the energy conservation spurred by high fuel prices.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The inflation adjusted real 2004 dollar value of oil fell from an average of $78.2 per barrel in 1981 to an average of $26.8 in 1986.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] This sentiment was echoed in November 1981, when the CEO of Exxon also characterized the glut as a temporary surplus, and that the word "glut" was an example of "our American penchant for exaggerated language".
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] He wrote that the main cause of the glut was declining consumption.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] In the United States, Europe and Japan, oil consumption had fallen 13% from 1979 to 1981, due to "in part, in reaction to the very large increases in oil prices by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and other oil exporters", continuing a trend begun during the 1973 price increases.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] After 1980, reduced demand and overproduction produced a glut on the world market, causing a six-year-long decline in oil prices culminating with a 46 percent price drop in 1986.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The U.S. reported negative economic growth during the 1970s and remained weak till the 1980s as the post World War II economic boom drew to a close.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Other causes that contributed to the recession included the Vietnam War, which turned out costly for the United States and the fall of the Bretton Woods system.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The emergence of newly industrialized countries rose competition in the metal industry, triggering a steel crisis, where industrial core areas in North America and Europe were forced to re-structure.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973–1974 stock market crash made the recession evident.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] According to the National Bureau of Economic Research, the U.S. economy slid into a recession in 1973–75.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Inflation levels remained high even when an economic expansion took place afterwards.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] During this recession, the Gross Domestic Product of the United States fell 3.2%.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Although the recession ended in March 1975, the unemployment rate did not peak for several months.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] In May 1975, the rate reached its height for the cycle of 9%.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The recession also lasted from 1973 to 1975 in the United Kingdom.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The GDP declined by 3.9% or 3.37% depending on the source.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] It took 14 quarters for the UK's GDP to recover to that at the start of recession.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] High oil prices in the 1970s induced investment in oil production by non-OPEC countries, particularly for reserves with a higher cost of production.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] These included Prudhoe Bay in Alaska, the North Sea offshore fields of the United Kingdom and Norway, the Cantarell offshore field of Mexico, and oil sands in Canada.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] As a result of the 1973 crisis many nations created strategic petroleum reserves (SPRs), crude oil inventories (or stockpiles) held by the governments of particular countries or private industry, for the purpose of providing economic and national security during an energy crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The International Energy Agency (IEA) was formed in the wake of this crisis and currently comprises 31 member countries.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] According to the IEA, approximately 4.1 billion barrels (650,000,000 m3) of oil are held in strategic reserves by the member countries, of which 1.4 billion barrels (220,000,000 m3) is government-controlled.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The remainder is held by private industry.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] These reserves are intended to be equivalent to at least 90 days of net imports.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Strategic Petroleum Reserve is one of the largest government-owned reserves, with a capacity of up to 713.5 million barrels (113,440,000 m3).
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Recently, other non-IEA countries have begun creating their own strategic petroleum reserves, with China being the second largest overall and the largest non-IEA country.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Since Israel's declaration of independence in 1948 this state has found itself in nearly continual conflict with the Arab world and some other predominantly Muslim countries.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The animosity between the Arabs and the Israelis became a global issue during the 1970s.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The Yom Kippur War of 1973, with the supplying of Israel by its Western allies while some Arab states received Soviet supplies, made this one of the most internationally threatening confrontations of the period.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The large oil discoveries in the Middle East gave some Muslim countries unique leverage in the world, beginning in the 1960s.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 and 1979 crises, in particular, were demonstrations of the new power that these countries had found.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The United States and other countries were forced to become more involved in the conflicts between these states and Israel.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] One of the first challenges OPEC faced in the 1970s was the United States' unilaterally pulling out of the Bretton Woods Accord and taking the U.S. off the established Gold Exchange Standard in 1971.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The change resulted in instability in world currencies and depreciation of the value of the U.S. dollar, as well as other currencies.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The revenues of OPEC also took a hit since they priced oil in dollars.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Finally OPEC started pricing oil against gold to combat the situation.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] But OPEC still struggled to maintain stability in the region as the negotiations between them and other Western oil companies bore little to no positive results.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] The major oil-producing regions of the U.S.—Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska—benefited greatly from the price inflation of the 1970s as did the U.S. oil industry in general.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Oil prices generally increased throughout the decade; between 1978 and 1980 the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent.
[src:automotive-industry/1970s-energy-crisis] Although all states felt the effects of the stock market crash and related national economic problems, the economic benefits of increased oil revenue in the Oil Patch states generally offset much of this.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The **2008–2010 automotive industry crisis** formed part of the 2008 financial crisis and the resulting Great Recession.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The crisis affected European and Asian automobile manufacturers, but it was primarily felt in the American automobile manufacturing industry.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The downturn also affected Canada by virtue of the Automotive Products Trade Agreement.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The automotive industry was weakened by a substantial increase in the prices of automotive fuels linked to the 2003–2008 energy crisis which discouraged purchases of sport utility vehicles (SUVs) and pickup trucks which have low fuel economy.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The popularity and relatively high profit margins of these vehicles had encouraged the American "Big Three" automakers, General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler to make them their primary focus.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] With fewer fuel-efficient models to offer to consumers, sales began to slide.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] By 2008, the situation had turned critical as the 2008 financial crisis placed pressure on the prices of raw materials.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Car companies from Asia, Europe, North America, and elsewhere implemented creative marketing strategies to entice reluctant consumers as most experienced double-digit percentage declines in sales.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Major manufacturers, including the Big Three and Toyota, offered substantial discounts across their product lineups.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Big Three faced criticism for their mix of available vehicle types offered, which faced criticism for being ill-suited to a climate of rising fuel prices.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] North American consumers turned to smaller, cheaper, more fuel-efficient imports from Japan and Europe.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In 2008, the Chinese government reduced automotive taxes in order to spur flagging sales.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In 2008, a plug-in hybrid version of the BYD F3 compact sedan was introduced, the world's first production model plug-in hybrid car.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In January 2009, Chinese auto-manufacturer Chery reported unprecedented monthly sales.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Citing falling production numbers, the State Bank of India reduced interest rates on automotive loans in February 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] For the first few months of 2009, Tata Motors conducted a widespread marketing campaign heralding the debut of the Tata Nano.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Billed as "the people's car", the manufacturer hopes the low cost will encourage customers to purchase the vehicle despite the ongoing credit crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] With high gas prices and a weak US economy in the summer of 2008, Toyota reported a double-digit decline in sales for the month of June, similar to figures reported by the Detroit Big Three.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] For Toyota, these were attributed mainly to slow sales of its Tundra pickup, as well as shortages of its fuel-efficient vehicles such as the Prius, Corolla and Yaris.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In response, the company has announced plans to idle its truck plants, while shifting production at other facilities to manufacture in-demand vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On December 22, 2008, Toyota declared that it expected the first time loss in 70 years in its core vehicle-making business.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Loss of $1.7 billion, in its group operating revenue, would be its first operating loss since 1938 (Company was founded in 1937).
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Toyota saw its sales drop 33.9 percent and Honda Motor by 31.6 percent.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On 5 December 2008 Honda Motor Company announced that it would be exiting Formula One race with immediate effect due to the 2008 economic crisis and are looking to sell the team.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Honda has predicted that there may be reductions among part-time and contract staff.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Upper management bonuses would also be reassessed and directors in the company will take a 10 percent pay cut effective January 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Nissan, another leading Japanese car manufacturer, announced that it also would be slashing production and will reduce its output by 80,000 vehicles in the first few months of 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In December 2008, Suzuki, Japan's fourth biggest car manufacturer, announced that it will cut production in Japan by about 30,000 units due to falling demand.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The company is expected to face its first profit drop in eight years for financial year ending in March 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Reported in Bloomberg on December 23, 2008, that Mitsubishi Motors is to widen production cuts on falling demand.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Japanese maker of Outlander sport-utility vehicles, will scrap the night shifts at two domestic factories as the deepening global recession saps auto demand.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The carmaker will halt the night shift at its Mizushima plant, excluding the minicar line.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Nighttime work at the Okazaki factory will stop from February 2.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The cuts are part of Mitsubishi's move to reduce planned output by 110,000 vehicles in the year ending March because of tumbling sales in Japan, the U.S. and Europe.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Japan's vehicle sales may fall to the lowest in 31 years in 2009, according to the country's automobile manufacturers association.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Mitsubishi will also halt production of passenger cars on every Friday next month at the Mizushima factory in western Japan.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Okazaki plant in central Japan will close every Saturday in January and for another five days.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Toyota, on December 22, 2008, slashed profit forecasts amid a sales slump.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Japanese automaker, often held up with Honda as a success story for the rest of the auto industry to follow, said it expected a slim profit margin of US$555 million for the year ending in March 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Toyota had originally been projecting a massive profit of $13.9 billion for that period.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Their sales in the United States were down 34 per cent and were down 34 per cent in Europe as well.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Facing its first loss in nearly sixty years, Toyota sought loans from the Japanese government.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On November 4, 2009, Toyota announced its immediate withdrawal from Formula One, ending the team's involvement in the sport after eight seasons.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] See also 2009–2010 Toyota vehicle recalls.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] South Korean automakers have been generally much more profitable than their US and Japanese counterparts, recording strong growth even in depressed markets such as the United States.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Despite a global economic slowdown, Hyundai-Kia successfully managed to overtake Honda Motor in 2008 as the world's 5th largest automaker, climbing eight rankings in less than a decade.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Hyundai-Kia continued its rapid success in 2009, when only a year after overtaking Honda, it surpassed Ford Motor as the world's 4th largest automaker.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Hyundai-Kia's continued success was unusual at a time when most automakers saw their sales falling sharply, with leading automaker GM even filing for bankruptcy.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Hyundai-Kia took significant advantage of the prolonged automotive crisis by producing affordable yet high quality and well designed vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Rapid globalization has seen state of the art factories being built in several countries including Slovakia, the United States and China.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The manufacturing facilities have been geared-up to build products that are designed and engineered for local markets.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Kia Cee'd is a leading example, being designed, developed and engineered in Germany and built in Slovakia.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Unlike others, this crisis turned into an opportunity for many South Korean automakers.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Korean automaker Hyundai offered customers who have lost their jobs to return a new-car purchase for a refund.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] South Korean automakers therefore had a competitive advantage against expensive luxury vehicles and SUVs from US, Japanese and German automakers.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] During the fourth quarter of 2008 to the first quarter of 2009, which was the height of this automotive crisis, the extremely weak South Korean won, especially against the US dollar and Japanese yen, significantly boosted the price competitiveness of South Korean exports in key markets.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Another factor that helped maintain this momentum was an increasingly improving brand awareness, attributable to the introduction of the country's own luxury vehicles such as the Hyundai Genesis and Hyundai Genesis Coupe, which received highly positive awards in the press and reviews.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Hyundai's brand grew by 9% in 2008, surpassing Porsche and Ferrari, while it used the Super Bowl football broadcast, the world's most expensive commercial air time, to promote the Hyundai brand in the United States.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Nonetheless, South Korean automakers were not completely immune to this automotive crisis and in December 2008 Hyundai Motor Company had begun reducing production at plants in the U.S., China, Slovakia, India and Turkey because of sluggish demand.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The company missed an earlier projection of 4.8 million units for 2008 and announced a freeze of wages for administrative workers and shortened factory operations as demand weakened amid the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] South Korea's fourth largest automaker, SsangYong Motor, owned by the Chinese automobile manufacturer SAIC (Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation), is the worst affected company in this crisis as it manufactures mainly heavy petroleum consuming SUVs.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The carmaker recorded its fourth straight quarterly losses by the end of 2008 with red ink of $20.8 million in the third quarter.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Also during the July to September period, sales dropped 63 percent to 3,835 vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Its production lines have been idle since December 17 as part of efforts to reduce its inventory.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The automaker has halted production twice previously this year.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In December 2008, SAIC gave an ultimatum to the SsangYong union to accept its restructuring plan or face the parent company's withdrawal, which, if implemented, would mean certain bankruptcy.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] A 70% share of *SsangYong* was acquired by India's Mahindra & Mahindra Limited in February 2011.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] However, the South Korean Ministry of Knowledge Economy said that there will be no liquidity provision at the government level for five automakers - Hyundai, Kia, GM Daewoo, Samsung Renault and Ssangyong."We have no plans to inject liquidity into the carmakers," a ministry official said.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] As part of Luxgen global expansion, the first overseas sale was made in Oman in 2010, with a plan to focus on the Middle East, Latin America, Central America and South America, Russia, mainland China and Southeast Asia car markets.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In Europe where car sales had also drastically decreased, consideration was being given to financial support for the automotive industry, particularly in France, Germany and Italy.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] German Foreign Minister Frank-Walter Steinmeier and Jean-Claude Juncker, Luxembourg's Prime Minister and head of the Eurogroup of single currency nations, discussed the possibility of a common rescue package to be agreed by all the EU member states.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] After 6 years of decline, in February 2014 car registration for a year increased to 894,730 vehicles and for subsequent 6 months the sales increased as expected with the price cuts and economic revival.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On November 20, 2008, French automobile manufacturer PSA Peugeot Citroen predicted sales volumes would fall by at least 10% in 2009, following a 17% drop in the current quarter.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] As a result, it planned to cut 2,700 jobs.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On 11 February 2009, PSA announced it would cut 11,000 jobs worldwide.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] However, none of these are expected to be in France.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Renault announced a net profit for 2008 of 599 million euros for the 2008 financial year.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] This was a 78% drop in profits from the 2007 financial year.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] European sales fell 4% and worldwide sales 7%, forcing Renault to abandon their 2009 growth targets.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] This however made Renault one of the few car makers to return a profit.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Renault consistently struggled to return profits in the 1990s.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On November 24, 2008, French President Nicolas Sarkozy and German Chancellor Angela Merkel agreed to support the crisis-stricken automobile industry in France and Germany.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On December 16, 2008 Fiat in Italy announced that it will extend its temporary plant closures in Italy by a month; the Pomigliano d'Arco, the main plant for its Alfa Romeo cars will be shut for four weeks.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] However, on February 20, 2009, reacting to actions by the Italian government to stimulate the automotive sector, Fiat said its plant closures would be curtailed.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The company also forecast that sales in Europe will drop by 14 percent in 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On January 20, 2009 the company announced that it had entered into an agreement, subject to regulatory approvals, to acquire 35% of Chrysler.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Chrysler would be accorded access to Fiat's sales outlets in Europe, while in reciprocation Fiat will also gain access to Chrysler's dealership network in the U.S., where it is predicted smaller models such as the Fiat Grande Punto may be successful.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In the past, Fiat has had trouble gaining a foothold in the American markets, whilst Chrysler has never held a strong market share in Europe since it sold its UK based Rootes Group and France based Simca to PSA Peugeot Citroen in the 1980s.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On January 22, 2009, Fiat announced a 19% drop in revenues in the last three months of 2008.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi said the government would meet to discuss the issue.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Russia's automotive industry was hit hard by the Late 2000s recession, which started from United States.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Production of passenger cars dropped from 1,470,000 units in 2008 to just 597,000 units in 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Lorry production fell from 256,000 to 91,000 in the same period.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In late 2008, the Russian government introduced protectionistic measures, worth $5 billion, to improve the situation in the industry.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] This included $2 billion's worth of bailouts for troubled companies and $3 billion credits to buyers of Russian cars.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Prime minister Vladimir Putin described the move as vital in order to save jobs.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The tariffs for imported foreign cars and trucks were increased to a minimum 50% and 100%, respectively.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The tariffs are linked to engine size of the vehicle.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The increased duties led to protests in Russian cities, most notably in Vladivostok, as the import of Japanese cars is an important sector of the city's economy.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The most efficient anti-crisis measure executed by the Russian government was the introduction of a car scrappage scheme in March 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Under the scheme, buyers of new cars can receive a subsidy which is 600,000 rubles ($20,000) at maximum.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Sales of Russia's largest carmaker Avtovaz doubled in the second quarter of 2010 as a result, and the company returned to profit.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Spanish automobile manufacturer SEAT (a subsidiary of the Volkswagen Group) cut production at its Martorell plant by 5% on 7 October 2008, due to a fall in general sales.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] This affected 750 employees and continued until July 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] SEAT is still continuing to install solar panels on its Martorell plant near Barcelona.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On December 11, 2008, the Swedish government provided its troubled auto makers, Volvo and Saab, with support amounting to SEK 28 billion (3.5 billion USD).
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The two companies had requested assistance, faced with the financial difficulties of their U.S. owners Ford and General Motors.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The plan consists of a maximum of SEK 20 billion in credit guarantees, and up to SEK 5 billion in rescue loans.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On 18 February 2009 General Motors warned Saab may fail within ten days, should the Swedish government not intervene.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On 20 February, an administrator was appointed to restructure Saab and assist in it becoming independent of its troubled parent General Motors.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] General Motors have confirmed their intention to sell their Swedish subsidiary, Saab.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Of Sweden's 9 million population, 140,000 work in the car industry and they account for 15% of exports.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In the United Kingdom, Jaguar Land Rover, now owned by Tata Motors, was seeking a $1.5 billion loan from the government to cope with the credit crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On 22 December 2008, Tata declared that it would inject "tens of millions" of pounds into the company it had acquired from Ford Motor Corporation in early 2008.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] British Prime Minister Gordon Brown also stated the intention to help out car industry in U.K.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On 8 January 2009, Nissan UK announced it was to shed 1200 jobs from its Washington, Tyne and Wear factory in North East England.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] This announcement was made, despite the plant recently being hailed as the most efficient in Europe.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] General Motors UK subsidiary Vauxhall Motors, whose brand is the second most popular in the UK has two bases in the UK, a factory in Ellesmere Port, Cheshire and their headquarters and design and development centre in Luton, Bedfordshire.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] It is as yet unknown whether these plants will be affected by the GM cutbacks.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The group along with their sister subsidiary, Opel of Germany, was supposed to be sold in their majority to Magna International, an Austro-Canadian company who supply many parts to large car companies, but General Motors cancelled the transaction.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] UK bus manufacturer Optare received an order from Arriva in November 2008 for the manufacture of 53 buses in a contract worth over £6million, securing 500 jobs at the company's Assembly factory in Cross Gates, Leeds, West Yorkshire and the parts centre in Cumbernauld, North Lanarkshire.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] UK Van and commercial vehicle manufacturer LDV Group asked the UK government for a £30 million bridging loan to facilitate a management buyout of the group.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] LDV has since said it has a viable future and intends to become the first volume producer of electric vans should the management buyout take place.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Production at LDV's factory in Birmingham, West Midlands (where it employed 850 staff) has been suspended since December 2008 due to falling demand.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Eventually, no buyout materialised and LDV was declared defunct on 15 October 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Along with several other countries, the UK government launched a *scrappage incentive scheme* in order to support the crisis stricken industry.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Cars registered prior to 31 July 1999, later extended to 29 February 2000, were eligible to be scrap in exchange for a discount of £2000 on a new car, half of which was provided by the government and the other half by the dealer.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The scheme came to an end on 31 March 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Canadian auto industry was closely linked to the U.S., due to the Automotive Products Trade Agreement and, later, the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), and experienced similar difficulties.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The crisis in the United States is mainly defined by the government rescue of both General Motors and Chrysler.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Ford secured a line of credit in case they require a bridging loan in the near future.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Car sales declined in the United States, affecting both US based and foreign car manufacturers.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The bridging loans led to greater scrutiny of the U.S. automotive industry in addition to criticism of their product range, product quality, high labour wages, job bank programs.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The government-backed rescue of the American auto industry gained the support of 37% of Americans in 2009 according to a CNN/Opinion Research Corporation poll, and it gained the support of 56% of Americans in 2012 according to a Pew Research Center poll.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Chrysler was forced into bankruptcy in April 2009 and GM in May.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] While the "Big Three" U.S. market share declined from 70% in 1998 to 53% in 2008, global volume increased particularly in Asia and Europe.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The U.S. auto industry was profitable in every year since 1955, except those years following U.S. recessions and involvement in wars.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] During these periods the companies incurred much legacy debt.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Facing financial losses, the Big Three have idled many factories and drastically reduced employment levels.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] GM spun off many of its employees in certain divisions into independent companies, including American Axle in 1994 and Delphi in 1999.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The spin-offs and other parts makers have shared Detroit's downturns, as have the U.S.-owned plants in Canada.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Altogether the parts makers employ 416,000 people in the U.S. and Canada.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] General Motors alone is estimated to have lost $51 billion in the three years before the start of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] GM is set to reacquire factories from its Delphi subsidiary during its Chapter 11 restructuring.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The 2005 Harbour Report estimated that Toyota's lead in benefits cost advantage amounted to $350 US to $500 US per vehicle over North American manufacturers.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The United Auto Workers agreed to a two-tier wage in recent 2007 negotiations, something which the Canadian Auto Workers has so far refused.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Delphi, which was spun off from GM in 1999, filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy after the UAW refused to cut their wages and GM is expected to be liable for a $7 billion shortfall.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In order to improve profits, the Detroit automakers made agreements with unions to reduce wages while making pension and health care commitments.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] GM, for instance, at one time picked up the entire cost of funding health insurance premiums of its employees, their survivors and GM retirees, as the U.S. did not have a universal health care system.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] With most of these plans chronically underfunded in the late 1990s, the companies have tried to provide retirement packages to older workers, and made agreements with the UAW to transfer pension obligations to an independent trust.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Nonetheless, non-unionized Japanese automakers, with their younger American workforces (and far fewer American retirees) will continue to enjoy a cost advantage.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Despite the history of their marques, many long running cars have been discontinued or relegated to fleet sales, as GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler shifted away resources from midsize and compact cars to lead the "SUV Craze".
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Since the late 1990s, over half of their profits have come from light trucks and SUVs, while they often could not break even on compact cars unless the buyer chose options.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Ron Harbour, in releasing the Oliver Wyman's 2008 Harbour Report, stated that many small "econoboxes" of the past acted as loss leaders, but were designed to bring customers to the brand in the hopes they would stay loyal and move up to more profitable models.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The report estimated that an automaker needed to sell ten small cars to make the same profit as one big vehicle, and that they had to produce small and mid-size cars profitably to succeed, something that the Detroit three have not yet done.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] SUV sales peaked in 1999 but have not returned to that level ever since, due to higher gas prices.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In the case of Chrysler Corporation, compact and mid-sized vehicles such as the Dodge Neon, Dodge Stratus and Chrysler Cirrus were produced profitably during the 1990s concurrently with more profitable larger vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] However, following the DaimlerChrysler merger in 1998, there was a major cost-cutting operation at the company.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The result was the lowering of benchmarked standards for Chrysler to aim at.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] This directly led to the following in Chrysler's case.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] There was realignment of the Chrysler Group model range with those of GM and Ford (i.e. a skew towards larger vehicles).
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Detroit Big Three had been slower to bring new vehicles to the market compared with foreign competitors.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Big Three have battled initial quality perceptions in spite of reports showing improvements.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Falling sales resulted in the Big Three's plants operating below capacity.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] GM's plants were operating at 85% in November 2005, well below the plants of its Asian competitors, and was only maintained by relying on cash incentives and subsidized leases.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Rebates, employee pricing, and 0% financing boosted sales but drained the automaker's cash reserves.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The subprime mortgage crisis and high oil prices of 2008 caused the popularity of once best-selling trucks and SUVs to plummet.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Automakers were forced to continue offering heavy incentives to help clear excess inventory.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Due to the declining residual value of their vehicles, Chrysler and GM stopped offering leases on most of their vehicles in 2008.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In September 2008, the Big Three asked for $50 billion to pay for health care expenses and avoid bankruptcy and ensuing layoffs, and Congress worked out a $25 billion loan.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] By December, President Bush had agreed to an emergency bailout of $17.4 billion to be distributed by the next administration in January and February.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In early 2009, the prospect of avoiding bankruptcy by General Motors and Chrysler continued to wane as new financial information about the scale of the 2008 losses came in.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Ultimately, poor management and business practices forced Chrysler and General Motors into bankruptcy.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Chrysler filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on May 1, 2009 followed by General Motors a month later.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] On June 2, General Motors announced the sale of the Hummer brand of off-road vehicles to Sichuan Tengzhong Heavy Industrial Machinery Company Ltd., a machinery company in western China, a deal which later fell through.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Later, GM announced that it was ending production of its Hummer, Saturn and Pontiac lines effective at the end of the 2009 model year.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Environmental politics and related concerns regarding carbon emissions have heightened sensitivity to gas mileage standards and environmental protection worldwide.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In a 2007 edition of his book *An Inconvenient Truth*, Al Gore criticized the Big Three.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] "They keep trying to sell large, inefficient gas-guzzlers even though fewer and fewer people are buying them." For example, Japan requires autos to achieve 45 miles per US gallon (5.2 L/100 km; 54 mpg‑imp) of gasoline and China requires 35 mpg‑US (6.7 L/100 km; 42 mpg‑imp).
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] By comparison, U.S. autos are required to achieve only 25 mpg‑US (9.4 L/100 km; 30 mpg‑imp) presently.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Other nations have adopted standards that are increasing mpg requirements in the future.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] When California raised its own standards, the auto companies sued.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Big Three received funding for a $25 billion government loan during October 2008 to help them re-tool their factories to meet new fuel-efficiency standards of at least 35 mpg‑US (6.7 L/100 km; 42 mpg‑imp) by 2020.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The $25 billion in loans from the Department of Energy to the auto manufacturers were actually authorized by Congress early this year but not funded.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In 2008, a series of damaging blows drove the Big Three to the verge of bankruptcy.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The Big Three had in recent years manufactured SUVs and large pickups, which were much more profitable than smaller, fuel-efficient cars.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Manufacturers made 15% to 20% profit margin on an SUV, compared to 3% or less on a car.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] When gasoline prices rose above $4 per gallon in 2008, Americans stopped buying the big vehicles and Big Three sales and profitability plummeted.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The 2008 financial crisis played a role, as GM was unable to obtain credit to buy Chrysler.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Sales fell further as consumer credit tightened and it became much harder for people with average or poor credit to obtain a bank loan to buy a car.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] During 2007, nearly 2 million new U.S. cars were purchased with funds from home equity loans.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Such funding was considerably less available in 2008.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] In addition, stock prices fell as shareholders worried about bankruptcy; GM's shares fell below 1946 levels.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Furthermore, the instability of the job market and individual consumers' finances discourages consumers who already have a working vehicle from taking on a new loan and payments, which affected almost all major manufacturers.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The annual capacity of the industry is 17 million cars; sales in 2008 dropped to an annual rate of only 10 million vehicles made in the U.S. and Canada.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] All the automakers and their vast supplier network account for 2.3% of the U.S. economic output, down from 3.1% in 2006 and as much as 5% in the 1990s.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] Some 20% of the entire national manufacturing sector is still tied to the automobile industry.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] The transplants can make a profit when sales are at least 12 million; the Big Three when sales are at least 15 million.
[src:automotive-industry/2008-2010-automotive-industry-crisis] By December 19, 2008, oil prices had fallen to $33.87 per barrel, but the automobile crisis continued.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The **2009–11 Toyota vehicle recalls** involved a series of global corrective actions to automobiles by the Japanese manufacturer, Toyota Motor Corporation.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Approximately 9 million vehicles were affected due to reports of sudden unintended acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The crisis, which affected Toyota's reputation, was initially attributed to mechanical defects: "pedal entrapment" caused by floor mats and "sticking accelerator pedals" resulting from friction in the pedal assembly.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] However, litigation in 2013 challenged these findings.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Expert testimony suggested that software problems in the car's Electronic Throttle Control System could trigger unintended acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The complex interplay of mechanical failures, software vulnerabilities, and regulatory scrutiny culminated in a significant safety event and penalties for the automaker.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The first recall occurred at the end of 2009 and the start of 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Toyota initiated the recalls, the first two with the assistance of the U.S.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), after reports that several vehicles experienced unintended acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The first recall, on November 2, 2009, was to correct a possible incursion of an incorrect or out-of-place front driver's side floor mat into the foot pedal well, which can cause pedal entrapment.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The second recall, on January 21, 2010, began after some crashes were shown not to have been caused by floor mat incursion.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] This latter defect was identified as a possible mechanical sticking of the accelerator pedal, causing unintended acceleration, which Toyota referred to as *Sticking Accelerator Pedal*.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Toyota initiated the original action in their *Defect Information Report*, dated October 5, 2009, amended January 27, 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Following the floor mat and accelerator pedal recalls, Toyota also issued a separate recall for hybrid anti-lock brake software in February 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] As of January 28, 2010, Toyota had announced recalls of approximately 5.2 million vehicles for the pedal entrapment/floor mat problem, and an additional 2.3 million vehicles for the accelerator pedal problem.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Approximately 1.7 million vehicles are subject to both.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Certain related Lexus models and the Pontiac Vibe (the Vibe being a General Motors-rebadged Toyota Matrix) were also affected.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The next day, Toyota widened the recall to include 1.8 million vehicles in Europe and 75,000 in China.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] By then, the worldwide total number of cars recalled by Toyota stood at 9 million.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Sales of multiple recalled models were suspended for several weeks as a result of the accelerator pedal recall, with the vehicles awaiting replacement parts.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] As of January 2010, 21 deaths were alleged due to the pedal problem since 2000, but following the January 28 recall, additional NHTSA complaints brought the alleged total to 37.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The number of alleged victims and reported problems sharply increased following the recall announcements, which were heavily covered by U.S. media, although the causes of individual reports were difficult to verify.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Government officials, automotive experts, Toyota, and members of the general public contested the scope of the sudden acceleration issue and the veracity of victim and problem reports.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Various parties attributed sudden unintended acceleration reports to mechanical, electric, and driver error causes.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Some U.S. owners that had their recalled vehicles repaired still reported accelerator pedal issues, leading to investigations and the finding of improper repairs.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recalls further led to additional NHTSA and Toyota investigations, along with multiple lawsuits.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 8, 2011, the NHTSA, in collaboration with NASA, released its findings into the investigation on the Toyota drive-by-wire throttle system.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] After a 10-month search, NASA and NHTSA scientists found no electronic defect in Toyota vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Driver error or pedal misapplication was found responsible for most of the incidents.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The report ended by stating, "Our conclusion is Toyota's problems were mechanical, not electrical." This included sticking accelerator pedals and pedals caught under floor mats.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] However, on October 24, 2013, a jury ruled against Toyota and found that unintended acceleration could have been caused due to deficiencies in the drive-by-wire throttle system or the Electronic Throttle Control System (ETCS).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Michael Barr of the Barr Group testified that NASA had not been able to complete its examination of Toyota's ETCS and that Toyota did not follow best practices for real time life-critical software, and that a single bit flip, which can be caused by cosmic rays could cause unintended acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] As well, the run-time stack of the real-time operating system was not large enough, and it was possible for the stack to grow large enough to overwrite data that could cause unintended acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] As a result, Toyota has entered into settlement talks with its plaintiffs.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On September 26, 2007, Toyota recalled 55,000 sets of heavy-duty rubber floor mats from the Toyota Camry and ES 350 sedans.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recalled mats were of the optional "all-weather" type.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] NHTSA stated that the recall was due to the risk that unsecured mats could move forward and trap the accelerator pedal.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On August 28, 2009, a two-car collision killed four people riding in a Lexus dealer-provided loaner ES 350 in San Diego, California.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The NHTSA released a safety investigation report on October 25, finding that the accident vehicle was wrongly fitted with all-weather rubber floor mats meant for the RX 400h SUV, and that these mats were not secured by either of the two retaining clips.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The brake hardware also showed signs of heavy braking consistent with a stuck accelerator pedal.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The report stated that the accelerator pedal's hinge did not allow for relieving obstructions, and the dashboard lacked directions for the three-second emergency press of the push button keyless ignition.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] NHTSA investigators also recovered the accident vehicle's accelerator pedal, which was still "bonded" to the SUV floor mat.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Another investigation conducted by the San Diego County Sheriff's Department found that three days before the crash, another customer had complained to the dealership about the floor mat trapping the same loaner car's accelerator pedal while driving.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The prior driver had switched to neutral and tugged on the floor mat, which released the accelerator.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On November 2, 2009, the NHTSA denied a petition to reopen previously closed unintended acceleration investigations of Toyota vehicles, stating they had already been thoroughly investigated making it unlikely for the NHTSA to reach any new conclusions.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Later that day Toyota issued a voluntary recall of 3.8 million vehicles, with a letter sent to owners asking them to remove the driver floor mat and not replace it with any other type of mat.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Toyota UK states that the floor mat recall affects U.S. models only.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On November 25, 2009, Toyota amended its floor mat recall involving the same 3.8 million vehicles sold in North America.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Toyota will reconfigure the accelerator pedal, replace the all-weather floor mats with thinner mats, and install a brake override system to prevent unwanted acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The brake override system, also called "brake to idle" and already a common design in German cars, allows the driver to override the accelerator by hitting the brakes.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In a follow-up statement, the NHTSA announced the November 25, 2009 recall details as a "vehicle-based remedy" to address the floor mat pedal issue.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In its November 25, 2009 announcement, Toyota stated that dealers would be instructed first on how to reshape the accelerator pedal for the repair.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Installation of the brake override began in January 2010 on Toyota Camry and Lexus ES 350 models, the vehicles with the most units included in the recall.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On January 21, 2010, Toyota initiated a second recall, this time in response to reports of accelerator pedals sticking in cars without floor mats.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The company had received three such complaints in 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The January 21 recall announcement for the accelerator pedal problem covered 2.3 million vehicles sold in the U.S.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Toyota then widened the recall to include 1.8 million vehicles in Europe and 75,000 in China.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On January 26, Toyota announced that until they had finalized an appropriate remedy to address the potential for sticking accelerator pedals, sales would be suspended for selected vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On January 31, 2010, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that U.S. regulators cleared Toyota's proposed repair for the pedals and the company would resume production by February 8.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 1, 2010, Toyota said that its dealers should get parts to fix the sticky accelerator pedal by the end of the week.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On January 29, 2010, the Toyota recall was extended to Europe and China.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The number of vehicles likely to be affected in Europe was unconfirmed but Toyota said it may reach up to 1.8 million.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] At the time of recall there had been 30 incidents involving the accelerator pedal problem in Europe.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On January 30, 2010, PSA Peugeot Citroën announced it was recalling cars built in a Czech Republic plant, Toyota Peugeot Citroën Automobile Czech, a joint venture with Toyota.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Although the company did not say when it would begin the recall, nor how many cars were affected, the plant in question, which produces the Peugeot 107, Citroën C1 and the Toyota Aygo, produces 200,000 cars a year.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 2, 2010, Toyota announced that the recalls could extend to Africa, Latin America, and the Middle East, where Toyota said it had sold a total of 180,000 vehicles, although the company did not specify how many might be affected by a recall.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 3, 2010, Toyota Australia announced that its accelerator pedals are made by a different supplier and that there is no need for a recall of Australian-made vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Automobile accelerator pedals have historically been mechanical assemblies that link the pedal to the engine throttle by mechanical linkages or a Bowden cable.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] With the advent of electronic throttle control, accelerator pedals consist of a spring-loaded pedal arm connected to an electronic transducer.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] This transducer, typically a potentiometer or Hall effect sensor, converts the position of the pedal arm to an electronic signal which is sent to an electronic control unit (ECU).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The older mechanically designed accelerator pedals not only provided a spring return, but the mechanism inherently provided some friction.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] This friction introduced mechanical hysteresis into the pedal force versus pedal position transfer function.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Put more simply, once the pedal was set at a specific position, the friction would help keep the pedal at this setting.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] This made it easier for the driver to maintain a pedal position.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] For example, if the driver's foot is slightly jostled by a bump in the road, the accelerator pedal tends to stay at its setting.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] While these old purely mechanical designs did have some friction, the return spring force was always designed to overcome this friction with a considerable safety margin.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The return spring force ensured that the throttle returned to zero if the pedal force applied by the driver was reduced or removed.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] With electronic accelerator pedals, there was little inherent friction because of the simplicity of the mechanical design.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The tactile pedal response of only a spring force with no hysteresis can make it more difficult for a driver to maintain an accelerator pedal position.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Manufacturers of electronic accelerator pedals designed their pedals with additional parts to recreate the tactile response of the older mechanical accelerator pedals.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The Toyota electronic accelerator pedals contain a special friction device made of nylon 4/6 or polyphenylene sulfide within the pedal assembly to recreate the tactile response of older pedals.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] According to the Toyota recall information, it is this device that, which in some instances, has been preventing the accelerator pedal from returning to zero.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] According to Toyota, the tactile response friction device in the affected Toyota electronic accelerator pedals sometimes creates too much friction.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] This excess friction either slows the pedal return or completely stops it.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In the worst case, once a pedal is pushed to a specific setting, it stays at the setting even if the driver removes their foot from the pedal.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Early reports, in March 2007, involved the Tundra pickup truck, which used nylon 4/6 in the friction lever.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Some questions and confusion exist if the Toyota explanation fully accounts for all instances of unintended acceleration involving Toyota vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In June 2010, Chrysler also recalled 35,000 Dodge and Jeep models for sticky accelerator pedals made by CTS Corporation.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Chrysler stated that the CTS pedals have pivot bushings that may dislodge, causing the accelerator to become stuck or slow to return to idle.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On whether braking alone may fail to stop affected vehicles, a driver account in the *Los Angeles Times* claimed that the attempt to stop a 2005 Camry was unsuccessful with both the brake and emergency brake.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The Camry's braking distances with a purposely stuck accelerator were also shorter than that of the Ford Taurus' regular stopping distance.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] *Car and Driver* concluded that, based on their emergency stopping tests, the Camry's brakes could overcome the accelerator in all cases even without a brake override, and that stopping distances with a wide-open throttle were largely indiscernible from regular braking.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In 2010, Edmunds.com also tested the stopping distances of a Toyota Camry SE V6 with a purposely stuck wide-open throttle.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Their tests found that the car's brakes could override a stuck accelerator and bring the car to a stop.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The German Commission on Technical Compliance (TÜV) of Rheinland also tested the stopping distance of Toyota iQ, Aygo, Yaris, Auris, Verso, Avensis, and RAV4 models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] With the accelerator purposely jammed to 80% of maximum speed, each vehicle was able to brake safely to a halt.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The TÜV findings indicated that each model met the legal requirements for deceleration and stopping distances, and that all Toyota models tested had brakes that could override a stuck accelerator.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 3, 2010, the NHTSA announced that it had received reports from 102 drivers of possible problems related to the braking system on the 2010 model year Toyota Prius, while an additional 14 such reports had been received in Japan.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Three of these reports claimed that brake problems had led to the car crashing, with one accident in July 2009 occurring when a Prius crashed head-on into another car injuring two people.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The Prius was not involved in Toyota's second recall, although it had been involved in the first recall involving floor mats.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Toyota said that it was investigating the reports, and that it would be "premature to comment." On February 3, 2010, the Japanese Transport Ministry began investigating the redesigned Prius, and Toyota said that it was aware of 77 Prius brake complaints in Japan.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 4, 2010, the NHTSA announced it had opened an investigation into the issues with the Prius's brakes, which Toyota said was caused by a software glitch.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The company said it was looking into the best way to solve the problem.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] An internal NHTSA memo indicated that the issue was the "short delay" in regenerative braking when hitting a bump, resulting in increased stopping distance.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 6, 2010, Toyota said that it had fixed the braking problem on Prius models built since late January 2010 via a software update for the ABS to improve brake response.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On the same day, a Japanese newspaper reported that Toyota had contacted dealers in Japan about their intent to recall all affected vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] While it was unclear if the same step would be taken elsewhere, American dealers had been told that Toyota was planning on repairing the vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 8, Toyota announced a voluntary global recall of 2010 model year Prius models produced through late January 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The affected vehicles will receive a software update for the brakes and its ABS system.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In total, Toyota recalled three hybrid vehicles to reprogram the anti-lock braking (ABS) software.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In February 2010, a U.S. federal grand jury in New York began the process of determining if there is probable cause to charge Toyota criminally for the way it has handled the Prius' brake recall, and a civil class action lawsuit has been filed on behalf of 2010 Prius hybrid owners.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] A total of 133,000 Prius vehicles in the U.S. and 52,000 in Europe are to receive the same software update.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] *Guardian.co.uk* reports that this affects the third-generation Prius built before January 27, 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 8, 2009, Toyota announced a recall of approximately 7,300 early 2010 model year 4-cylinder Camrys due to the possibility of the power steering hose rubbing into the front brake line which may cause a brake fluid leak.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 3, 2010, Toyota recalled approximately 153,000 vehicles from model years 2005 to 2011 for failing to comply with requirements of FMVSS 110, "Tire Selection and Rims", due to missing load-carrying capacity labels.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 12, 2010, Toyota recalled approximately 8,000 2010 model year 4WD Tacoma trucks for potential front drive shaft issues.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recall involves inspecting a drive shaft component which if cracked will be replaced.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The Tacoma pickups were built between mid-December 2009 and early February 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Most affected vehicles have not been sold.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Another recall for frame corrosion recall was confined to the following model(s): MY 2000–2003 Toyota Tundra.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] According to Toyota USA, frame corrosion could allow spare tires or the fuel tank to fall off the vehicle.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On July 7, 2010, Toyota recalled 270,000 Lexus and Crown vehicles worldwide for improperly manufactured valve springs.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] According to Toyota, the condition can cause rough idling and potential engine stalling.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recall concerns brake fluid leakage from the master cylinder (U.S. market and non-U.S. marketed Toyota Crown and Lexus GS350) and an electrical problem with the fuel pump, which would cause engine stalling (all markets except the U.S.).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On October 10, 2012, Toyota announced a recall of 7.43 million vehicles (2.47 million in the US, 460,000 in Japan, 1.39 million in Europe, and 3.11 million in other markets) worldwide.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In the U.S. the recall affects MY 2005-2010 Yaris, Corolla, Matrix, Camry, RAV4, Highlander, Tundra, and Sequoia as well as Scion xB and xD.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In Japan, the recall affects MY 2005-2010 Vitz, Belta, Ractis, Ist, and Corolla Rumion.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In Europe, the recall affects MY 2005-2010 Yaris, Corolla, Auris, Camry, and RAV-4.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Vehicles in overseas markets are also affected.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recall concerns a problem with the driver's side power window switch that "sticks" and could lead it to melt or catch fire.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] It is "not something that would cause any deadly accidents like the recall of 2009" and repairs include the application of a special fluorine grease to the switch.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On January 30, 2013, Toyota announced a recall of one million vehicles in the US.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recall affects 752,000 MY 2003-2004 Corolla and Corolla Matrix models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recall concerns the airbag module, which can cause the airbag to inflate improperly.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Toyota also announced a recall affecting 270,000 MY 2006-2012 Lexus IS models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] This recall concerns loose nuts on the wiper blades, which can cause the wipers to fail, especially if there is a heavy buildup of snow.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On March 15, 2013, Toyota announced a recall of 209,000 vehicles in the US.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recall affects MY 2007-2013 FJ Cruiser models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The recall concerns the driver and front passenger seat belt retractors, which can come loose, especially if the rear doors are slammed repeatedly.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Numerous investigations have taken place, including those by the U.S.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] NHTSA and the Japanese transport ministry.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The difficulty of investigations is compounded by the fact that driver error can be a possibility in certain cases.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* reported, "Even when dealers and automakers suspect driver error, it is difficult for them to outright blame their customers for fear of alienating them or appearing insensitive", which *USA Today* also suggested.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In another U.S. incident, on December 26, 2009, four people died in Southlake, Texas, a suburb of Dallas, when their 2008 Toyota Avalon sped off the road and through a fence, landing upside down in a pond.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The car's floor mats were found in the trunk of the car, where owners had been advised to put them as part of the recall.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] According to the police report, the driver suffered from epilepsy, but investigators could not rule out either a vehicle defect or the possibility that the driver had suffered a seizure.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On Feb 17, 2010, U.S. safety regulators launched an investigation into Corolla steering complaints.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On March 14, 2010, the Norwegian government considered whether to ban Prius cars from roads in Norway pending an investigation after a near-fatal incident involving a senior citizen.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On March 29, after receipt of technical and other information, police indicted the driver involved in the Prius incident for making "a false emergency call to police".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] NHTSA data shows that there was an annual average of 26 abrupt acceleration reports in the 1999–2001 Toyota Camry and Lexus ES models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] This number increased by more than 400% to a total of 132 annually in 2002–2004 models, which were designed with new electronic throttles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In 2004, the NHTSA launched a probe of throttle control systems on around 1 million Lexus and Toyota sedans.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] After several months of investigating, the NHTSA said it found no evidence of a defect and no data was indicating any bad parts.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Christopher Santucci, an employee of Toyota's Washington, D.C. office and an NHTSA employee until he was hired by Toyota in 2003, testified that he was informed by the NHTSA in March 2004 about the pending investigation over unintended acceleration complaints.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] According to Santucci in his deposition, his former NHTSA colleagues decided not to investigate some incidents involving acceleration lasting longer than 1 second.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The decision to exclude certain incidents from the investigation reduced the significance of the issue to the NHTSA at least on paper.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] However, in 2005, 2006 and 2008, Toyota customers again asked the NHTSA to investigate uncontrolled acceleration from electronic throttle controls and power steering issues.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Although there were hundreds of complaints, the NHTSA found no evidence of defects; and in every case, Toyota provided data it said showed no such evidence.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On November 2, 2009, the NHTSA denied a petition to reopen previously closed unintended investigations of Toyota vehicles, stating they were unlikely to reach any new conclusions.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In February 2010, however, NHTSA was again looking into the electronic throttle control systems on Toyota vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In February 2010, State Farm insurance revealed that it had warned NHTSA in late 2007 on an increased trend of Toyota accidents related to the recalled models; other insurers stated however that they had not seen such a trend.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On June 1, 2010, the NHTSA opened an investigation into reports that floor mats were jamming accelerators in Ford Fusion and Mercury Milan sedans.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On June 30, 2010, NHTSA reported on its latest broad study of unintended acceleration on all car makes, including Toyota, in conjunction with NASA and the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] NHTSA stated that it was unable to find electronic throttle defects, but identified floor mat entrapment and pedals that were slow to return to idle as two causes of Toyota complaints.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] NHTSA also stated it could only verify one Toyota unintended acceleration accident caused by a vehicle defect.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On July 14, 2010, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that NHTSA investigations of 75 accidents alleged to sudden acceleration in Toyota vehicles had found driver error as the primary cause in all but one case attributed to floor mats.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Black box recorder data found that during these crashes, the throttle was open and brakes not pressed.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On July 30, *The Wall Street Journal* quoted the former head of NHTSA's Recall Management Division stating that the investigation "has become very political", with Department of Transportation officials "hoping against hope that they find something that points back to a flaw".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Although the NHTSA study finding driver error was reportedly complete, DOT officials had blocked its release.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 8, 2011, NASA and the NHTSA announced the findings of a ten-month study concerning the causes of the Toyota malfunctions of 2009.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] According to their findings, there were no electronic faults in the cars that could have caused the sudden-acceleration problems.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] "The jury is back, the verdict is in: There is no electronic-based cause for unintended high-speed acceleration in Toyotas, period," Transportation Department Secretary Ray LaHood declared in the LA Times.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Hiroko Tabuchi writing in *The New York Times* claims that problematic vehicles may have been accurately reported in Japan due to police correctly blaming driver error, as no verified unintended acceleration case exists.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism (MLIT) released its findings of sudden acceleration complaints in February 2010, finding that of the 134 cases logged by the ministry between 2007 and 2009, Toyota accounted for 38 cases (28.3% of all reported).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Because Toyota's market share was approximately 27.8% of all passenger cargo vehicles, the MLIT noted that no particularly unusual rate was found among these complaints.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The House Oversight and Government Reform Committee and the House Energy and Commerce Committee held hearings in February 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Retired social worker Rhonda Smith testified before Congress that her car accelerated out of control but the NHTSA investigator determined that a misplaced floor mat had caused the problem; the subsequent owner of the car reported no trouble after driving the car over 27,000 miles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In a February 2010 letter to Toyota, U.S. congressional investigators "said a review of consumer complaints produced by Toyota shows that company personnel identified sticking pedals or floor mats as the cause of only 16 percent of the unintended acceleration reports".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Several media reports later claimed that Toyota had announced that the recalls will not completely solve the accelerator pedal problems.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] On February 24, 2010, Toyota responded that it "has rigorously tested its solutions" and is "confident" with the recall repairs, but that it would continue to monitor other possible contributing factors for unintended acceleration, including mechanical, electronics, and driver error.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] In early 2010, the U.S. government began considering requiring all vehicles sold in the U.S. to have accelerator override built into their brake systems.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Research groups have questioned whether Toyota would "get off easily" because of its large investment in lobbying in Washington, with close ties to the congressional representatives who will lead inquiries into the company's string of safety problems.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] Other publications noted that half the Democratic congressional members involved in the hearings had received campaign contributions from the United Auto Workers union, a major stockholder of Toyota's top U.S. rival, General Motors.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p01] The letter also noted there were "16.4 million recalls in the auto industry for 2009", "many as serious or more serious" than Toyota's recall.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Toyota stopped producing vehicles on certain production lines for the week of February 1, 2010, to assess and coordinate activities.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The North America vehicle production facilities affected were located in Cambridge and Woodstock, Ontario, Canada (where Corolla, Matrix, and RAV4 models are produced), Princeton, Indiana (Highlander and Sequoia), Georgetown, Kentucky (Avalon and Camry), and San Antonio, Texas (Tundra).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In addition to recalling vehicles, Toyota announced that it would install brake override systems on all Lexus, Scion and Toyota vehicles by the end of 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On February 3, 2010, United States Transportation Secretary Ray LaHood advised owners of vehicles affected by the recall to "stop driving" their vehicles until they can be fixed by a dealer.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The recall came at a difficult time for Toyota, as it was struggling to emerge from the recession and had already suffered from a resultant decrease in sales, and the low exchange rate from yen to US dollars.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On the day the recall was announced in the US, it was also announced that 750 jobs would be cut at Toyota's British plant at Burnaston, near Derby.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Also, it was estimated that each Toyota dealership in the U.S. could lose between US$1.75 million to US$2 million a month in revenue, a total loss of US$2,470 million across the country from the entire incident.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Additionally, Toyota Motors as a whole announced that it could face losses totaling as much as US$2,000 million from lost output and sales worldwide.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Between 25 January and 29 January 2010 Toyota shares fell in value by 15%.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] According to analysts, Toyota owners (including owners of cars not recalled) may also be economically affected by the recall, as the damage to Toyota's reputation could negatively affect the resale value of used cars.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Industry analysts noted that the recall response was a challenge for The Toyota Way manufacturing philosophy, because the recalled parts were not due to factory errors or quality control problems, but rather to design issues leading to consumer complaints.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] As a result, better communication of consumer issues with management was needed, and so the global quality committee aimed to be more responsive to consumer concerns.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] One day after Toyota's announced sales suspension General Motors began offering a US$1,000 cash rebate targeted toward Toyota owners.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] By February 1, 2010 Ford, Chrysler, and Hyundai were offering similar incentives.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In February 2010, a motion for retrial was submitted on behalf of a Minnesota man, Koua Fong Lee, who, in 2008, was sentenced to eight years in jail for rear-ending a car, killing three of the five occupants and injuring the other two.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] This happened in June 2006 when he was driving home from church with his family and exiting the highway.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Koua insists that his 1996 Toyota Camry sped up to between 70 and 90 mph (110 and 140 km/h) despite heavy braking.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In May 2010, a vehicle inspector hired by attorneys for the convicted man reported finding problems with the car's accelerator system.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] At least two of the jurors from the 2008 trial questioned the guilty verdict, and one of the injured survivors filed suit against Toyota and the local dealership that sold the car, stating that he believed Lee should be set free.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In June 2010, the Ramsey County Attorney and prosecutor Susan Gaertner opposed a new trial, stating that she saw no evidence that Koua's Camry experienced "sudden unintended acceleration", and a U.S.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] District Court Judge was given until September 2010 to decide whether or not Lee should be re-tried.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In August 2010, the judge ruled that Lee would be re-tried, but the prosecutor declined to prosecute.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Before the ruling, Gaertner offered Lee release with the condition that he would still have a felony conviction on his record, barring him from driving privileges for ten years, and that he would be jailed if arrested for anything else.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Later that month, a Minnesota judge freed Lee from prison and Gaertner said she would immediately drop the charges.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The following week of February 1–7, 2010, the story reached #2, at 11% of all news coverage.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On February 10, Toyota dealers in the five-state Southeast region pulled all advertising from ABC stations in protest of "excessive" reporting on the Toyota recalls.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On March 5, the Associated Press described "relentless media coverage" of the recalls from news outlets.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] During the height of the recall crisis, Toyota came in for extensive criticism.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Editorials criticizing alleged disproportionate coverage of the recalls ran in *Automotive News*, *AutoWeek*, *BusinessWeek*, *Car and Driver*, *Motor Trend*, *Popular Mechanics*, and the *National Post*.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Such editorials commonly faulted media outlets for leaving out alternative explanations such as driver inattentiveness, driver skills, DUI, being on the cellphone, erroneous perceptions, reckless driving, or texting as causes of accidents.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In one cited example, the *Los Angeles Times* did not mention that an alleged Toyota runaway driver was indicted for vehicular manslaughter and driving under the influence of marijuana.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On March 8, 2010, a 2008 Prius allegedly uncontrollably accelerated to 94 miles per hour on a California Highway (US), and the Prius had to be stopped with the verbal assistance of the California Highway Patrol as news cameras watched.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The incident received national news coverage, with initial reporting including inaccurate information about the event, such as the claim that a CHP car was used to physically block Sikes' vehicle.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Subsequent investigations uncovered suspicious information about the alleged runaway Prius driver, 61-year-old James Sikes, including being US$19,000 behind in his Prius car payments and with US$700,000 in accumulated debt.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Sikes stated he wanted a new car as compensation for the incident.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Further government investigator tests on Sikes's Prius reportedly showed that the brake wear were consistent with intermittent braking, not constant hard braking as he claimed.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Sikes also reportedly had a history of false police reports, suspect insurance claims, theft and fraud allegations, and television aspirations.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] These findings raised questions about "the credibility of Mr.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Sikes' reporting of events" in a Congressional memo.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] According to a Rasmussen poll released on February 8, 2010, Toyota was viewed favorably by 59% and unfavorably by 29%.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The poll also found 72% of Americans have followed the recent Toyota news stories "somewhat closely" and 31% "very closely".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] A second Rasmussen poll released on February 12 found 23% of Americans believe the federal government is criticizing Toyota to aid General Motors of which it is the majority owner, 38% disagreed, and 39% were unsure.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On November 25, 2009, ABC News quoted Sean Kane, head of the for-profit firm *Safety Research & Strategies*, stating that he had uncovered hundreds of "non-floor mat sudden acceleration cases" which the floor mat recall did not address.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Kane, who works with attorneys suing Toyota, said his firm had discovered over 2,000 Toyota sudden acceleration cases involving 16 deaths and 243 injuries, publishing its most comprehensive report on the issue on Feb 5th, 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Kane alleged that the problem was not with the accelerator pedals, but with the electronic throttle control systems (ETC).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] An electronic throttle control system is a drive-by-wire system, in which the accelerator pedal and the engine are indirectly linked electronically, instead of directly linked mechanically.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] This means that input from the accelerator pedal is just one input used to decide how wide the throttle is opened.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* reported that since Toyota and Lexus began installing electronic throttle control systems in 2001, complaints of unintended acceleration with vehicles from both those brands rose sharply.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Electromagnetic interference with the electronic throttle control system is another possible cause of unintended acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Some speculated that cosmic rays, or radiation from outer space, was a possible source for alleged electronic malfunctions.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] 8, 2010, the NHTSA and NASA concluded the electronics were not to blame after reviewing the electronics and electromagnetic interference.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The finding was based on studying over 280,000 lines of software coding on nine vehicles involved in earlier sudden acceleration incidents.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] And studying the throttle systems at NASA's Langley Research Center and Chrysler's Auburn Hills headquarters.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In January 2021, engineer Colin O'Flynn was able to induce unintended acceleration with components from a Toyota vehicle using electromagnetic fault injection (EMFI) on a test bench.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] He used an ECU and components from a wrecked 2005 Toyota Corolla.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] O'Flynn's experiments were conducted without access to the ECU source code, and without access to the confidential report by the Barr Group.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On February 22, 2010, ABC News broadcast a report which demonstrated how unintended acceleration could be caused by inducing a short circuit in the throttle control.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Gilbert, a professor of automotive technology at Southern Illinois University Carbondale, was shown in a late-model Avalon with ABC News reporter Brian Ross.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] By "inducing a short" in an unspecified circuit, Gilbert was able to cause the Avalon to accelerate dramatically.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] After the car was stopped, a diagnostic tool connected to the car's ECU displayed no fault code.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Gilbert, the proper design of the ETC should not have permitted a short like the one he induced to open the throttle; the ECU should have detected a fault and cut the throttle.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Tests on GM vehicles, Gilbert said, did not expose a similar flaw.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] *Autoblog'*s analysis queried the test's real-world accuracy, noting that the short circuit method was not disclosed outside of wiring normally independent sensors together, the ECU could not be expected to detect unrealistic scenarios, and questioning ABC News' and Brian Ross's objectivity.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] *Autoblog* also uncovered that Gilbert was being paid by parties in lawsuits against Toyota.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Toyota responded by inviting ABC News to be present at its evaluation of the test.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On March 8, 2010, Toyota held a live news conference where its engineers demonstrated the same short circuit method on Ford, Chevrolet, Chrysler, and BMW vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In each case, engineers were able to induce the same dramatic acceleration with no ECU fault code.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Stanford's Center for Automotive Research stated that ABC News' demo was unrealistic and misleading.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] A study by Exponent Inc. finding that the short circuit "would be highly unlikely to occur naturally" and could "only be contrived in the laboratory" was also issued.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Toyota further demonstrated how Gilbert had allegedly shaved away wiring insulation, cut wires in the ETC, re-spliced them in a particular sequence, and added a control switch.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Gilbert's financial motive, being paid by Sean Kane, was also questioned.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] *AutoWeek,* Edmunds.com, and other automotive sources saw the conference as debunking ABC News' claims.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On March 11, 2010, ABC News further admitted to faking part of its report after tachometer screenshots were posted online.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The freeze-frames showed the parking brake, open-door, and seat belt warning lights on while the car was allegedly "accelerating" to 6,000 RPM, indicating that the car was actually not moving.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Media blog Gawker.com posted the photos and stated, "the tachometer footage is faked".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] ABC News claimed that it was "impossible to get a good picture of the tachometer" during the actual test, and re-edited the footage.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Gawker.com responded that the edited video was even more "staged".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The Associated Press added that the falsified footage "created ethical questions".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In February 2010, multiple media reports claimed that Apple Inc. co-founder Steve Wozniak had suggested that faulty software may be part of the problem.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] However, in a subsequent CNN interview, Wozniak stated, "I haven't really said those things.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Instead, Wozniak said his comments were about a "minor" cruise control issue on one of his several Priuses, and regarding other recalls, "whether it was mats, whether it was a sticky accelerator pedal, whatever – I believe they found the right solution.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Automotive journalist John Voelcker's analysis of Wozniak's description blamed the issue on user error, and not being familiar with the design differences of the adaptive cruise control system.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Some Prius users have also suggested erroneous user input explanations.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Others have come forward with their own stories about erratic vehicle behavior while using their cruise control.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In March 2010, *Ward's Auto* reported that user unfamiliarity with the faster response of laser- and radar-based cruise control systems was a likely factor according to AAA, NHTSA, and manufacturer findings.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In August 2010, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that experts at the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration had examined the "black boxes" of 58 vehicles involved in sudden-acceleration reports.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The study found that in 35 of the cases, the brakes weren't applied at the time of the crash.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In nine other cases in the same study, the brakes were used only at the last moment before impact.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On March 10, 2010, *The New York Times* ran an opinion piece by Richard Schmidt, professor emeritus of psychology at University of California Los Angeles and sudden acceleration researcher, suspecting driver error as the primary cause of unexplained Toyota sudden acceleration reports.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Schmidt pointed to several factors that make driver error more likely: elderly driver age, lack of experience with the car, and short stature.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In addition, unexplained sudden acceleration events were most frequently reported as occurring at low speed or fully stopped.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The resulting unexpected sudden acceleration would lead to panic, with the driver thinking that the acceleration system had failed.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The immediate response would be to brake hard, but not knowing that their foot was on the accelerator, pressing down caused greater acceleration.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In such panic situations, the driver would think that the brakes were not responding, and continue pressing on the accelerator pedal until they crashed.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Switching to neutral or turning off the ignition was typically not contemplated.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Incidents occurred exclusively in automatic transmission-equipped cars with driver complaints involving rental cars being far more frequent.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] All factors point to reduced driver familiarity and sophistication.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Also noted was that drivers with Type II diabetes (adult onset), which is more common among the elderly, are subject to reduced sensation in their lower extremities (peripheral neuropathy) with related impairment in positional knowledge of foot placement (proprioception).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] *Wired* wrote that since investigators have been "unable to find evidence supporting drivers' claims their Toyotas suddenly raced out of control" operator error is the most likely explanation.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] However, victims and relatives of sudden acceleration cases are commonly unwilling to suspect involved loved ones, and blame the vehicle instead.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] While many alleged cases lack exact details, over half of the reported incidents occurred from a complete stop or low speed, providing a window for the pedal misapplication to occur.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] A prior GM study found that 60- and 70-year-olds were six times more likely to experience sudden acceleration than 20- to 30-year-olds.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In *The New York Times*, Richard Schmidt concluded that a brake override system could prevent acceleration cases where a vehicle defect existed, but would not prevent sudden acceleration cases caused by pedal misapplication.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In February 2011, the findings of a 10-month-long study conducted by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), aimed to identify the main cause of sudden acceleration in Toyota and Lexus models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Congress and "enlisted NASA engineers with expertise in areas such as computer-controlled electronic systems, electromagnetic interference, and software integrity".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The most common problem was drivers hitting the accelerator pedal when they thought they were hitting the brake, which the NHTSA called "pedal misapplication." Of the 58 cases reported, 18 were dismissed out of hand.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Consumers in the U.S. and Canada have filed numerous class action lawsuits blaming the sudden acceleration problem on the electronic throttle control system (ETC) and alleging Toyota's negligence.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] As of February 26, 2010, there were at least 72 lawsuits pending in U.S. federal courts against Toyota or its subsidiaries as a result of the 2009-10 recalls.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Plaintiffs are seeking damages for personal injury or wrongful death resulting from accidents in the defective Toyota vehicles (in other words, product liability), loss of resale value, or a drop in the value of shares held by Toyota shareholders.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Toyota has retained the law firm of Alston & Bird to defend most of these cases.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation ordered consolidation of all federal actions into the Central District of California before Judge James V.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Selna for all pretrial motions and discovery.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The following week, Judge Selna set a May 13 initial scheduling conference at his courtroom in Santa Ana, California.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] He also appointed Cari Dawson, chairwoman of Alston & Bird's class action department, as lead counsel for defendants.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On May 14, after reviewing submissions from dozens of plaintiffs' attorneys, Judge Selna issued an order establishing which attorneys would be granted the potentially lucrative positions of lead counsel for the plaintiffs.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] First, he named nine attorneys as lead counsel for the economic loss cases and nine attorneys as lead counsel for the personal injury and wrongful death cases.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] He then named nine of the attorneys from these two panels to form a core discovery committee.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Three additional attorneys were named as liaisons to coordinate discovery with pending state court actions and other related federal litigation in progress outside of the MDL, like shareholder litigation.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Finally, one additional attorney was named as a consultant on behalf of international Toyota consumers.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Prominent attorneys appointed on the plaintiffs' side included Steve Berman of Hagens Berman Sobol Shapiro (on the personal injury and wrongful death committee) and Elizabeth Cabraser of Lieff Cabraser (on the economic loss committee).
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Selna also clarified the roles of defense counsel by appointing Cari Dawson and Lisa Gilford of Alston & Bird as lead counsel in the economic loss cases and Vince Galvin and Joel Smith of Bowman and Brooke as lead counsel in the personal injury and wrongful death cases.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Gilford and Galvin were also appointed to serve as lead defense liaisons to other related cases in federal and state courts.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On June 1, 2010, Judge Selna issued another order setting out a discovery schedule.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] He ordered both sides to make initial discovery disclosures by July 2, 2010, and set out a briefing schedule for motions concerning the consolidated complaints, with oral arguments set for November 19, 2010.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On July 1, 2010, Judge Selna appointed two retired Presiding Justices of the California Court of Appeal as special masters: John K.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Toyota has also been sued for not having a brake override system on older models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Edgar Heiskell, an attorney involved with one of the lawsuits, contends that electromagnetic interference with the electronic throttle control system is to blame for acceleration cases.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Heiskell contends that Toyota models as old as 2002 are also affected.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] According to him, "Toyota can't tell you that the '07 Camry they are recalling is any different from the '06 or the '03 that has the same throttle control in it." According to *The Wall Street Journal*'s Holman W.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On December 26, 2012, Toyota announced it would spend more than US$1 billion to settle a class action lawsuit involving unintended acceleration by retrofitting vehicles with safety devices and compensated owners for lost resale value.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] A confidential settlement was reached in a lawsuit against Toyota involving the injury of Jean Bookout and the death of Barbara Schwarz in November 2013.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On March 19, 2014, it was announced that Toyota and the U.S.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Justice Department had reached an agreement whereby Toyota would pay a US$1.2 billion criminal penalty in exchange for deferred prosecution of wire fraud charges.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The agreement also subjects the car company to further independent monitoring of its safety procedures.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The penalty ended a four-year investigation in which the Justice Department concluded that Toyota had intentionally hidden information about safety defects from the public and had made deceptive statements to protect its brand image.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Holder Jr. remarked "Other car companies should not repeat Toyota's mistake.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] A recall may damage a company's reputation, but deceiving your customers makes that damage far more lasting." The penalty is the largest ever waged against a car company.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In a statement, Toyota called the agreement difficult, but "a major step toward putting this unfortunate chapter behind us".
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] The company said it has made fundamental changes in its corporate structure and safety procedures since the investigation started.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Brake-override systems are now standard on all Toyota vehicles.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] As of March 2014, several civil wrongful death and personal injury lawsuits were pending.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Toyota is not the only automobile manufacturer that has issued recalls for unintended acceleration problems.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In December 2009, *Consumer Reports* analyzed 2008 model year NHTSA data for sudden acceleration among Toyota, Ford, Chrysler, GM, Honda, and Nissan, finding 52 complaints involving Toyota vehicles or 41% of complaints among these makes, and every other major car maker is affected.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] *Consumer Reports* noted that the media publicity around Toyota led to an increase in complaints for 2008 models.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] According to NPR's analysis of the NHTSA database, Jaguar, Volvo, and Honda also had high complaints depending on year.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] In February 2010, Edmunds.com released its findings on a review of all NHTSA complaints from 2001 to the present day, conducted in light of the Toyota recall crisis.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] Edmunds.com also noted that any individual can file a NHTSA complaint without providing a Vehicle Identification Number (VIN), which can lead to misleading statistics as "not all NHTSA complaints are created equal" and range from legitimate to nonsensical.
[src:automotive-industry/2009-2011-toyota-vehicle-recalls-p02] On June 5, 2010, NHTSA shut down online access to its complaint database following revelations of redundant, unverifiable entries and improperly secured personal data.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:automotive-industry/3d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Other common names for abalone are ear shells, sea ears, and, now rarely, muttonfish or muttonshells in parts of Australia, ormer in the United Kingdom, perlemoen in South Africa, and pāua in New Zealand.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Most abalone vary in size from 20 mm (0.8 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (8 in).
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The largest species, *Haliotis rufescens*, reaches 300 mm (12 in).
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The shells of abalone have a low, open spiral structure, and are characterized by several open respiratory pores in a row near the shell's outer edge.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The thick inner layer of the shell is composed of nacre, which in many species is highly iridescent, giving rise to a range of strong, changeable colors which make the shells attractive to humans as ornaments, jewelry, and as a source of colorful mother-of-pearl.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The shell of abalone is convex, rounded to oval in shape, and may be highly arched or very flattened.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The shell of the majority of species has a small, flat spire and two to three whorls.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The last whorl, known as the body whorl, is auriform, meaning that the shell resembles an ear, giving rise to the common name "ear shell".
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] *Haliotis asinina* has a somewhat different shape, as it is more elongated and distended.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The shell of *Haliotis cracherodii cracherodii* is also unusual as it has an ovate form, is imperforate, shows an exserted spire, and has prickly ribs.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] A mantle cleft in the shell impresses a groove in the shell, in which are the row of holes characteristic of the genus.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] These holes are respiratory apertures for venting water from the gills and for releasing sperm and eggs into the water column.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] They make up what is known as the selenizone, which forms as the shell grows.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] This series of eight to 38 holes is near the anterior margin.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The older holes are gradually sealed up as the shell grows and new holes form.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Each species has a typical number of open holes, between four and 10, in the selenizone.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The aperture of the shell is very wide and nacreous.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The exterior of the shell is striated and dull.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The color of the shell is very variable from species to species, which may reflect the animal's diet.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The iridescent nacre that lines the inside of the shell varies in color from silvery white, to pink, red and green-red to deep blue, green to purple.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The animal has fimbriated head lobes and side lobes that are fimbriated and cirrated.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The radula has small median teeth, and the lateral teeth are single and beam-like.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] They have about 70 uncini, with denticulated hooks, the first four very large.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The rounded foot is very large in comparison to most molluscs.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The soft body is coiled around the columellar muscle, and its insertion, instead of being on the columella, is on the middle of the inner wall of the shell.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The gills are symmetrical and both well developed.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] These snails cling solidly with their broad, muscular foot to rocky surfaces at sublittoral depths, although some species such as *Haliotis cracherodii* used to be common in the intertidal zone.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone reach maturity at a relatively small size.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Their fecundity is high and increases with their size, laying from 10,000 to 11 million eggs at a time.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The spermatozoa are filiform and pointed at one end, and the anterior end is a rounded head.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The adults are herbivorous and feed with their rhipidoglossan radula on macroalgae, preferring red or brown algae.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Sizes vary from 20 mm (25⁄32 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (7+7⁄8 in), while *Haliotis rufescens* is the largest of the genus at 30 cm (12 in).
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The haliotid family has a worldwide distribution, along the coastal waters of every continent, except the Pacific coast of South America, the Atlantic coast of North America, the Arctic, and Antarctica.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The majority of abalone species are found in cold waters, such as off the coasts of New Zealand, South Africa, Australia, Western North America, and Japan.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone are members of the clade Vetigastropoda, though their precise position within the clade is uncertain.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Despite their inclusion in the order Lepetellida, they do not appear to be particularly closely related to other members of the order and may be more closely related to Trochoidea, or alternatively outside of a clade uniting Trochoidea with the rest of Lepetellida.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The earliest known fossil abalone are known from the Campanian age of the Late Cretaceous.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The few known Cretaceous abalone fossils have all been found in North America, suggesting that the group may have originated there, although other possibilities have been suggested, including a central Indo-Pacific origin based on where abalone are most diverse today.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Haliotidae may have evolved from the pleurotomariidan families Temnotropidae or Trochotomidae.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] *Trochotoma frydai*, from the Campanian of Spain, closely resembles the Cretaceous abalone *Haliotis antillesensis* except in having a slit instead of a row of tremata.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The shell of the abalone is exceptionally strong and is composed of a tightly packed calcium carbonate matrix.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Layered among the matrix is an endogenous protein further strengthening the shell.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Due to the unique structure of the shell, a force applied directly to the shell matrix will more likely cause the shedding of layers as opposed to cracking or shattering.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Material scientists are currently studying this structure for insight into stronger ablative protective tools such as body armor.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The dust created by grinding and cutting abalone shell is dangerous; appropriate safeguards must be taken to protect people from inhaling these particles.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone are subject to various infectious diseases.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The Victorian Department of Primary Industries said in 2007 that ganglioneuritis killed up to 90% of stock in affected regions.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone possess very little clotting factor, meaning even a mild to moderate skin-piercing injury can result in death from fluid loss.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Members of the Spionidae of the polychaetes are known as pests of abalone.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone have been harvested for seafood and aesthetics since prehistory.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone shells and associated materials, like their claw-like pearls and nacre, have been used as jewelry and for buttons, buckles and inlay.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] These shells have been found in archaeological sites around the world, ranging from 100,000-year-old deposits at Blombos Cave in South Africa to historic Chinese abalone middens on California's Northern Channel Islands.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] For at least 12,000 years, abalone were harvested to such an extent around the Channel Islands that shells in the area decreased in size four thousand years ago.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Aquafarming of abalone as a meat product began in the late 1950s and early 1960s in Japan and China.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Since the mid-1990s, there have been many increasingly successful endeavors to commercially farm abalone for the purpose of consumption.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Overfishing and poaching have reduced wild populations to such an extent that farmed abalone now supplies most of the abalone meat consumed.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The principal abalone farming regions are Mainland China, Taiwan, Japan and South Korea.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone is also farmed in Australia, Canada, Chile, France, Iceland, Ireland, Mexico, Namibia, New Zealand, South Africa, Spain, Thailand and the United States.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] After trials in 2012, a commercial "sea ranch" was set up in Flinders Bay, Western Australia, to raise abalone.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The ranch is based on an artificial reef made up of 5,000 separate concrete abalone habitat units, which can host 400 abalone each.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The reef is seeded with young abalone from an onshore hatchery.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The abalone feed on seaweed that grows naturally on the habitats; the ecosystem enrichment of the bay also results in growing numbers of dhufish, pink snapper, wrasse, and Samson fish among other species.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone have long been a valuable food source for humans in every area of the world where a species is abundant.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The meat of this mollusc is considered a delicacy in certain parts of Latin America (particularly Chile), France, New Zealand, East Asia and Southeast Asia.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In the Greater China region and among overseas Chinese communities, abalone is commonly known as *bao yu*, and sometimes forms part of a Chinese banquet as one of the four sea delicacies of Chinese cuisine.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In the same way as shark fin soup or bird's nest soup, abalone is considered a luxury item, and is traditionally reserved for celebrations.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In Japan, live and raw abalone are used in sushi (known as *awabi*) or served steamed, salted, boiled, chopped, or simmered in soy sauce.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Salted, fermented abalone entrails are the main component of *tottsuru*, a local dish from Honshū.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In South Korea, abalone is called *Jeonbok* and used in various recipes.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] *Jeonbok* porridge and pan-fried abalone steak with butter are popular, but it's also commonly used in soups or ramyeon.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In California, US, abalone meat can be found on pizza, sautéed with caramelized mango, or in steak form dusted with cracker meal and flour.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] As abalone became more popular and less common, the prices adjusted accordingly.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In the 1920s, a restaurant-served portion of abalone, about 4 ounces (110 g), would cost (in inflation adjusted dollars) about US$7; by 2004, the price had risen to US$75.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In the United States, prior to this time, abalone was predominantly eaten, gathered, and prepared by Chinese immigrants.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Before that, abalone were collected to be eaten, and used for other purposes by Native American tribes.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] By 1900, laws were passed in California to outlaw the taking of abalone above the intertidal zone.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] This forced the Chinese out of the market and the Japanese perfected diving, with or without gear, to enter the market.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone started to become popular in the US after the Panama–Pacific International Exposition in 1915, which exhibited 365 varieties of fish with cooking demonstrations, and a 1,300-seat dining hall.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Tasmania supplies about 25% of the yearly world abalone harvest.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Around 12,500 Tasmanians recreationally fish for blacklip and greenlip abalone.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] For blacklip abalone, the size limit varies between 138 mm (5.4 in) for the southern end of the state and 127 mm (5.0 in) for the northern end of the state.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Greenlip abalone have a minimum size of 145 mm (5.7 in), except for an area around Perkins Bay in the north of the state where the minimum size is 132 millimetres (5.2 in).
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] With a recreational abalone licence, the bag limit is 10 per day, with a total possession limit of 20.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Scuba diving for abalone is allowed, and has a rich history in Australia.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] (Scuba diving for abalone in the states of New South Wales and Western Australia is illegal; a free-diving catch limit of two is allowed).
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Victoria has had an active abalone fishery since the late 1950s.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The state is sectioned into three fishing zones, Eastern, Central and Western, with each fisher required a zone-allocated licence.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Harvesting is performed by divers using surface-supplied air "hookah" systems operating from runabout-style, outboard-powered boats.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] While the diver seeks out colonies of abalone amongst the reef beds, the deckhand operates the boat, known as working "live" and stays above where the diver is working.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Bags of abalone pried from the rocks are brought to the surface by the diver or by way of "shot line", where the deckhand drops a weighted rope for the catch bag to be connected then retrieved.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Divers measure each abalone before removing from the reef and the deckhand remeasures each abalone and removes excess weed growth from the shell.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Since 2002, the Victorian industry has seen a significant decline in catches, with the total allowable catch reduced from 1440 to 787 tonnes for the 2011/12 fishing year, due to dwindling stocks and most notably the abalone virus ganglioneuritis, which is fast-spreading and lethal to abalone stocks.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Sport harvesting of red abalone is permitted with a California fishing license and an abalone stamp card.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In 2008, the abalone card also came with a set of 24 tags.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] This was reduced to 18 abalone per year in 2014, and as of 2017 the limit has been reduced to 12, only nine of which may be taken south of Mendocino County.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Legal-size abalone must be tagged immediately.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone may only be taken using breath-hold techniques or shorepicking; scuba diving for abalone is strictly prohibited.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Taking of abalone is not permitted south of the mouth of San Francisco Bay.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] A size minimum of 7 in (180 mm) measured across the shell is in place.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] A person may be in possession of only three abalone at any given time.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] As of 2017, abalone season is May to October, excluding July.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Transportation of abalone may only legally occur while the abalone is still attached in the shell.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Sale of sport-obtained abalone is illegal, including the shell.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Only red abalone may be taken, as black, white, pink, flat, green, and pinto abalone are protected by law.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In 2018, the California Fish and Game Commission closed recreational abalone season due to dramatically declining populations.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] That year, they extended the moratorium to last through April 2021.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Afterwards, they extended the ban for another 5 years until April 2026.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In December 2025 California extended the ban another 10 years until April 2036.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] An abalone diver is normally equipped with a thick wetsuit, including a hood, bootees, and gloves, and usually also a mask, snorkel, weight belt, abalone iron, and abalone gauge.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Alternatively, the rock picker can feel underneath rocks at low tides for abalone.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone are mostly taken in depths from a few inches up to 10 m (33 ft); less common are freedivers who can work deeper than 10 m (33 ft).
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone are normally found on rocks near food sources such as kelp.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] An abalone iron is used to pry the abalone from the rock before it has time to fully clamp down.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Divers dive from boats, kayaks, tube floats, or directly off the shore.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The largest abalone recorded in California is 12.34 in (31.3 cm), caught by John Pepper somewhere off the coast of San Mateo County in September 1993.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The mollusc *Concholepas concholepas* is often sold in the United States under the name "Chilean abalone", though it is not an abalone, but a muricid.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In New Zealand, abalone is called *pāua* (/ˈpaʊə/, from the Māori language).
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] *Haliotis iris* (or blackfoot pāua) is the ubiquitous New Zealand pāua, the highly polished nacre of which is extremely popular as souvenirs with its striking blue, green, and purple iridescence.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] *Haliotis australis* and *Haliotis virginea* are also found in New Zealand waters, but are less popular than *H. iris*.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] *Haliotis pirimoana* is a small species endemic to Manawatāwhi / the Three Kings Islands that superficially resembles *H. virginea*.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Like all New Zealand shellfish, recreational harvesting of *pāua* does not require a permit provided catch limits, size restrictions, and seasonal and local restrictions set by the Ministry for Primary Industries (MPI) are followed.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The legal recreational daily limit is 10 per diver, with a minimum shell length of 125 mm (4.9 in) for *H. iris* and 80 mm (3.1 in) for *H. australis*.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In addition, no person may be in possession, even on land, of more than 20 pāua or more than 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) of pāua meat at any one time.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Pāua can only be caught by free-diving; it is illegal to catch them using scuba gear.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] An extensive global black market exists in collecting and exporting abalone meat.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] This can be a particularly awkward problem where the right to harvest pāua can be granted legally under Māori customary rights.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] When such permits to harvest are abused, it is frequently difficult to police.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The limit is strictly enforced by roving Ministry for Primary Industries fishery officers with the backing of the New Zealand Police.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Poaching is a major industry in New Zealand with many thousands being taken illegally, often undersized.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Convictions have resulted in seizure of diving gear, boats, and motor vehicles and fines and in rare cases, imprisonment.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] There are five species endemic to South Africa, namely *H. parva*, *H. spadicea*, *H. queketti* and *H. speciosa*.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The largest abalone in South Africa, *Haliotis midae*, occurs along roughly two-thirds of the country's coastline.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone-diving has been a recreational activity for many years, but stocks are currently being threatened by illegal commercial harvesting.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In South Africa, all persons harvesting this shellfish need permits that are issued annually, and no abalone may be harvested using scuba gear.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] For the last few years, however, no permits have been issued for collecting abalone, but commercial harvesting still continues as does illegal collection by syndicates.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In 2007, because of widespread poaching of abalone, the South African government listed abalone as an endangered species according to the CITES section III appendix, which requests member governments to monitor the trade in this species.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] This listing was removed from CITES in June 2010 by the South African government and South African abalone is no longer subject to CITES trade controls.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Export permits are still required, however.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The abalone meat from South Africa is prohibited for sale in the country to help reduce poaching; however, much of the illegally harvested meat is sold in Asian countries.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] As of early 2008, the wholesale price for abalone meat was approximately US$40.00 per kilogram.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] There is an active trade in the shells, which sell for more than US$1,400 per tonne.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Ormers (*Haliotis tuberculata*) are considered a delicacy in the British Channel Islands as well as in adjacent areas of France, and are pursued with great alacrity by the locals.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] This, and a recent lethal bacterial disease, has led to a dramatic depletion in numbers since the latter half of the 19th century, and "ormering" is now strictly regulated to preserve stocks.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The gathering of ormers is now restricted to a number of 'ormering tides', from 1 January to 30 April, which occur on the full or new moon and two days following.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] No ormers may be taken from the beach that are under 80 millimetres (3.1 in) in shell length.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Gatherers are not allowed to wear wetsuits or even put their heads underwater.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Any breach of these laws is a criminal offence and can lead to a fine of up to £5,000 or six months in prison.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The demand for ormers is such that they led to the world's first underwater arrest, when Mr.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Kempthorne-Leigh of Guernsey was arrested by a police officer in full diving gear when illegally diving for ormers.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The highly iridescent inner nacre layer of the shell of abalone has traditionally been used as a decorative item, in jewelry, buttons, and as inlay in furniture and musical instruments, such as on fret boards and binding of guitars.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] See article Najeonchilgi regarding Korean handicraft.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone has been an important staple in a number of Indigenous cultures around the world, specifically in Africa and on the Northwest American coast.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The meat is a traditional food, and the shell is used to make ornaments; historically, the shells were also used as currency in some communities.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Abalone are critically threatened due to overfishing and the acidification of oceans as lower pH erodes the calcium carbonate in their shells.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] In the 21st century, white, pink, and green abalone are on the United States federal endangered species list.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Possible restoration sites have been proposed for the San Clemente Island and Santa Barbara Island areas.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Reintroduction of farming abalone to the wild has been proposed, with these abalone having special tags to help track the population.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The number of species that are recognized within the genus *Haliotis* has fluctuated over time, and depends on the source that is consulted.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The number of recognized species range from 30 to 130.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] As of 2025, 76 extant species and 25 fossil species were listed as accepted in MolluscaBase.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] This list finds a compromise using the WoRMS database, plus some species that have been added, for a total of 57.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] The majority of abalone have not been rated for conservation status.
[src:automotive-industry/abalone] Those that have been reviewed tend to show that the abalone in general is an animal that is declining in numbers, and will need protection throughout the globe.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:automotive-industry/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
